---

<ElementLayout
  title="ruby"
  description="Represents a ruby annotation, used for East Asian typography."
  elementName="ruby"
  category="native"
  nativeGroup="Text Semantics"
  currentPath="/docs/elements/native/ruby/"
>
  <section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;ruby&gt;</code> element represents a ruby annotation. Ruby annotations are small text above or beside the base text, typically used to show pronunciation of East Asian characters (like furigana in Japanese or pinyin in Chinese).</p>
    <p>A ruby annotation consists of the base text and the ruby text (<code>&lt;rt&gt;</code>), with optional fallback parentheses (<code>&lt;rp&gt;</code>) for browsers that don't support ruby.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Basic Example</h2>
    <div class="example">
      <ruby>
        漢 <rp>(</rp><rt>かん</rt><rp>)</rp>
        字 <rp>(</rp><rt>じ</rt><rp>)</rp>
      </ruby>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Basic ruby example">{basicRubyCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Japanese Furigana</h2>
    <p>Ruby is commonly used to show furigana (pronunciation guides) for kanji:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <p>
        <ruby>東京<rp>(</rp><rt>とうきょう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>は日本の首都です。
      </p>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Japanese furigana">{japaneseCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Chinese Pinyin</h2>
    <p>Ruby can also display pinyin for Chinese characters:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <p>
        <ruby>
          北京 <rp>(</rp><rt>Běijīng</rt><rp>)</rp>
        </ruby>
        is the capital of China.
      </p>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Chinese pinyin">{chineseCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Multiple Ruby Annotations</h2>
    <p>Multiple ruby elements in a sentence:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <p>
        <ruby>明日<rp>(</rp><rt>あした</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>の
        <ruby>天気<rp>(</rp><rt>てんき</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>は
        <ruby>晴<rp>(</rp><rt>は</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>れです。
      </p>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Multiple ruby">{multipleRubyCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Styling Ruby</h2>
    <p>Ruby annotations can be styled with CSS:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Styled ruby">{styledRubyCode}</code-block>
    <p>The <code>ruby-position</code> property controls whether annotations appear above (<code>over</code>) or below (<code>under</code>) the base text.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Attributes</h2>
    <p>This element supports <a href="/docs/elements/native/states/">global attributes</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <p>Screen readers may read both the base text and ruby text, or just one depending on the implementation. The ruby text provides pronunciation information that benefits learners and those with reading difficulties. The <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> fallback ensures that in unsupported browsers, the annotation appears in parentheses.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Related Elements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/rt/"><code>&lt;rt&gt;</code></a> - The ruby text (annotation)</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/rp/"><code>&lt;rp&gt;</code></a> - Fallback parentheses for non-supporting browsers</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</ElementLayout>
